eign spouse': Binational marriages and the impact of family-related migration policies on gender relations -- tSection IV. Transnational family lives and practices -- t12. Transnational family life and female migration in Italy: One or multiple patterns? -- t13. Civic stratification, stratified reproduction and family solidarity: Strategies of Latino families in Milan -- t14. Gender and intergenerational issues in the circulation of highly skilled migrants: The case of Indian IT professionals -- t15. Negotiating transnational caring practices among migrant families -- tList of contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFamily-related migration is moving to the center of political debates on migration, integration, and multiculturalism in Europe. Still, strands of academic research on family migrations and migrant families remain separate from-and sometimes ignorant of-each other. This volume seeks to bridge the disciplinary divide. Collectively, the authors address the need to better understand the diversity of family-related migration and its resulting family forms and practices, to question simplistic assumptions about migrant families in public discourse, to study family migration from a mix of disciplinary perspectives, and to acknowledge the state's role in shaping family-related migration, practices, and lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEurope -- Emigration and immigration -- Government policy -- 21st century. 0aEurope -- Emigration and immigration -- Social aspects -- 21st century. 0aImmigrant families -- Social aspects -- Europe -- 21st century. 0aImmigrants -- Family relationships -- Europe. 0aTransnationalism -- Government policy -- Europe -- 21st century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aB